title: For Sale:  Stevens Break-Action 12 Gauge WALL HANGER MANTLE GUN
postcontent:
So, I bought this nice Stevens model 311 double barrel 12 gauge at a gun show recently.

I brought it home, shot it, took it skeet shooting and it was GREAT FUN until the thing broke after 100-200 shells. 

Oh well, it was fun for a while.

The issue is the piece that pushes the firing pins back snapped from old age/fatigue. Now the firing pins are permanently in the forward position as they'd be right after firing a round (or two). They don't go back. Because of this, the gun doesn't open or function.

This is still a cool old gun (1957 made according to the date code) that is beautiful and would look great over someones mantle. I'd keep it for that purpose but as I'm sure you can understand, I'd rather NOT look at it.

Still has many uses however:

1) Fix it... I'm sure theres parts out there somewhere, or maybe this is weldable. Gun has a shiny bore thats in great shape, and shoots really well... atleast it did.

2) Mantle Gun

3) Gun-Shaped club for Home Defense. Even tho its not currently operational, it would still suck to get hit over the head with this thing.

Asking $175 obo. Would consider possible trades for 7.62x54R ammo, or 5.45x39 as well. Possibly 12 gauge ammo for ya know, the guns I *HAVENT* broken yet. Might be willing to trade for another Mosin and I may be willing to add cash to this 12 gauge for the right deal.

Email only.

Even tho this thing needs some work, its still technically a firearm, so bring your valid Ohio drivers license with you.

title: For Sale:  1905 Winchester
postcontent:
So I have a rather unique rifle here. Many of you have probably never seen one or heard of one. Its a Winchester model 1905 semi-automatic rifle. It and it's variants were only produced for 15 years (a total of about 30,000 were made). The Model 1905 was only made for 2 years! before it was replaced by the 1907 (which was a larger caliber). It was designed from the rim fire model 1903. The gun is significant because it was Winchester's FIRST semi-automatic center-fire gun. Its a semi-automatic 5 round box magazine (which I have). 
It shoots a .35 WSL which stands for Winchester Self Loading. This round is not to be confused with .35 whelen or .35 Remington or .351 wsl. This ammo is very hard to find most people have never heard of it. It is not sold in stores.  Sometimes people will list the ammo on forums and armslist and not realize what they have and you can get a great deal on it. I do actually have ammo for it. I have roughly 60 rounds. If your interested in the gun I will tell you were I get my ammo. The ammo I buy is safe and reliable its made using new materials but made to original specs. Where I get my ammo is not too pricey either... comparable to shooting a 30-06 cost wise. I personally don't think the ammo is hard to find. You just have to order it instead of picking it up in the store.

Do a google search of the gun and read what ever you can its a very interesting gun. A lot of prison guards and police officers used them. 

This gun is very early it was made in 1905 Pre WW1 its nearly 110 years old. Serial number is 1xxx. Its a great piece of history.

Makes a great small game gun too. I used it for coyote, raccoon, possum from time to time.

I can send pictures via text or email
(513) 706-793zero
Price is flexible and includes all the ammo I have.

This barrel is an "AR Stoner," from a time when they were using ER Shaw barrel blanks. The profiling, fluting, threading, and installation of stainless extension were by AR Stoner.

I did a very lengthy break-in, and only ever used high quality lapped 5.56. It was snaked every 20 rounds or less, and meticulously cleaned after every ~100 rounds. I am intending to build a Rem 700 in 300wm or maybe a 416 barrett, so mid range precision is obsolete for me if I have a platform easily able to reach twice the effective distance of 5.56, thus making this barrel unnecessary for me.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith & Wesson Model 67-1 DAO
postcontent:
This .38 Special stainless revolver was a police gun out west before it came to Virginia, and the DAO in the subject line is not a typo. This revolver is Double Action Only, but the gunsmith who did the job left the spur on the hammer. It was a professional job and did not affect the smoothness of the action in any way.

Whoever carried it dinged the cylinder quite a bit. There are also scratches on the frame and some light pitting under the grips. However, the bore and cylinder chambers are very nice. The action is smooth and locks up as it should.

The grips on it are factory new production, but it will also come with the black plastic Hogue monogrip that used to be on it. A HKS speedloader is also included.

Overall this revolver is in excellent working condition with some cosmetic issues. These pre-lock pieces are getting to be a pain to find, but I can't justify having more than one S&W in this caliber.

Asking $430.

I think he may have fired only 10 or 15 rounds through it and then it sat in his desk drawer for 50 years.  Rarely carried, always in a soft leather holster.

Serial number shows 1961 manufacture, which means it's just over 50 years old and qualifies as a Curio/Relic exempt from the new law. In the 1960s, Warren Center developed an unusual break-action, single-shot pistol that later became known as the Contender in his basement workshop. Meanwhile, the K.W. Thompson Tool Company had been searching for a product to manufacture year-round. In 1965, Warren Center joined the K.W. Thompson Tool Company, and together, they announced Warren Center's Contender pistol in 1967. Although it sold for more than comparable hunting revolvers, the flexibility of being able to shoot multiple calibers by simply changing out the barrel and sights and its higher accuracy soon made it popular with handgun hunters. title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson Springfield Armory 12ga Pump Shotgun
postcontent:
Nice older S&W model 916T shotgun with 19" vent-rib barrel and full choke.  I'm told that these were manufactured by Springfield Armory for Smith and Wesson.  It is marked: " Eastfield Model 916-T", "MFG. by Smith & Wesson", Springfield, Mass., USA", " Proof Tested 12 GA", and "3 inch Chamber, Full Choke".  This is the take-down model, so with a simple twist of the magazine tube nut the barrel can be turned a quarter turn and lifted out of the receiver.  The wood is nice Walnut.  The nice part about these shotguns is that the receiver is steel, not aluminum like a lot of later pumps.  The action works very smoothly and locks up tight.  It also produces a pellet pattern.  It's chambered for 3" shells.  The bluing is worn on the receiver, less so on the barrel.  The bore is bright and shinny, and there is no rust anywhere on the shotgun.  I think the tube holds 5 rounds with plug removed.  

Price if firm, and I'm not interested in trades at this time.  

Please include a contact phone number to rull out the scammers.  E-mails without a working phone number will be deleted.  So will e-mails asking simply if I still have it.  If this listing is still active, then I still have it.

Thanks for looking!
